body:
Hello @scordio, @joel-costigliola,

I took a quick look over this one. The issue seems to be in [Introspection::getPropertyGetter](https://github.com/assertj/assertj/blob/4c2d0b1b9dfb6b00c76f55fd155a0a2c844285bc/assertj-core/src/main/java/org/assertj/core/util/introspection/Introspection.java#L72) where we catch all exceptions and wrap them within a _IntrospectionError_ which is later treated as if the field is not present.

If the getters throw an exception, this will be wrapped within an InvocationTargetException_. So, what we can do is check the exception - if needed - rethrow it without wrapping it in our [IntrospectionError](https://github.com/assertj/assertj/blob/4c2d0b1b9dfb6b00c76f55fd155a0a2c844285bc/assertj-core/src/main/java/org/assertj/core/util/introspection/IntrospectionError.java#L21)

```java
try {
      getter.setAccessible(true);
      getter.invoke(target);
} catch (InvocationTargetException t) {
      // if getter invocation fails, throw different exception that is not caught by our logic
      throw new GetterInvocationError(formatErrorMessage("Encountered exception when invoking getter for %s in %s", propertyName,
                                                         target), t.getCause());
} catch (Exception t) {
      // same as it currently works:
      throw new IntrospectionError(formatErrorMessage("Unable to find property %s in %s", propertyName, target), t);
}
```

If this solution seems reasonable, I can raise a PR so you can take a better look into it :) 
Let me know what you think.

@joel-costigliola - This will be even simpler than I initially thought. 
We only need to have a different catch block for `InvocationTargetException` and wrap it into a different runtime ex:

```diff
try {
      getter.setAccessible(true);
      getter.invoke(target);
+ } catch (InvocationTargetException t) {
+       //  if getter invocation fails, throw a different exception that's not caught by our logic
+       throw new GetterInvocationError(formatErrorMessage(
+                 "Encountered exception when invoking getter for %s in %s", propertyName, target), t.getCause());
+
} catch (Exception t) {
      throw new IntrospectionError(formatErrorMessage("Unable to find property %s in %s", propertyName, target), t);
}
```

With this change, we'll still use the field as a fallback verification - **but only when the getter invocation fails for reflection-related reasons**. _Basically, for all the other exceptions described [here](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/reflect/Method.html#invoke(java.lang.Object,%20java.lang.Object...)), apart from InvocationTargetException_

---

On the other hand, I've noticed tests suggesting the original intended behavior was to bypass **ANY** exception thrown by the getter and verify the field:

For eg: [FieldsOrPropertiesExtractor_extract_Test::should_fallback_to_field_if_exception_has_been_thrown_on_property_access](https://github.com/assertj/assertj/blob/4c2d0b1b9dfb6b00c76f55fd155a0a2c844285bc/assertj-core/src/test/java/org/assertj/core/groups/FieldsOrPropertiesExtractor_extract_Test.java#L107)

In other words, if the getter throws an error we'll check for the field. If the field is also missing (the case described in this issue), we'll return the non-existent property assertion error, swallowing the exception.

So I guess it's a matter of deciding what the correct behavior would be in this case.

As things stand, we initially try to invoke the getter: If there is any sort of exception (regardless if it's a reflection-related exception in the lib or if it's an exception in the tested code, in the getter itself), we'll try to verify the field as a fallback. 

As a result, the behaviour related to invoking the getters seems a bit inconsistent:

```java
static class MyPojo {
  private String name = "abcd";
  private String address = "abcd";
  private String country = "abcd";

  public String getName() {
    throw new RuntimeException("some exception");
  }
  public String getAddress() {
    return "something else";
  }
  String getCountry() {
    return "something else";
  }
}

@Test
void test() {
  assertThat(new MyPojo()).hasFieldOrPropertyWithValue("name", "abcd"); // <-- this is passing, is it ok?
  assertThat(new MyPojo()).hasFieldOrPropertyWithValue("address", "abcd"); // <-- this is failing
  // off-topic:
  assertThat(new MyPojo()).hasFieldOrPropertyWithValue("country", "abcd"); // <-- this is passing, package-protected getters are ignored
}
```

As I understand, we want to keep maintaining this behavior, not to introduce a breaking change - correct? 

_If I understand your comment correctly, it is what you have done, right ?_
Not yet, but yes - we can go into this direction. Please confirm if I got it right: 
 - maintain current behavior 
 - if the field is also missing, rethrow the original exception produced by the getter

---

_PS: Another interesting case I found (and maybe a bit unexpected/counterintuitive) is with the package-protected getters which will always be ignored, but seems to be slightly off-topic here._
